    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>String are immutable in Java. You can't change them.</p>\n\n<p>You need to create a new string with the character replaced.</p>\n\n<pre><code>String myName = \"domanokz\";\nString newName = myName.substring(0,4)+'x'+myName.substring(5);\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>Or you can use a StringBuilder:</p>\n\n<pre><code>StringBuilder myName = new StringBuilder(\"domanokz\");\nmyName.setCharAt(4, 'x');\n\nSystem.out.println(myName);\n</code></pre>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 471844,
      "reputation" : 562,
      "user_id" : 879891,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 100,
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/6e0d973506ebd5ca91f406a236eabc3d?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG&f=y&so-version=2",
      "display_name" : "no name",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/879891/no-name"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 25,
    "last_activity_date" : 1591506779,
    "last_edit_date" : 1591506779,
    "creation_date" : 1312527612,
    "answer_id" : 6952610,
    "question_id" : 6952363,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p><code>String</code> is an immutable class in java. Any method which seems to modify it always returns a new string object with modification.</p>\n\n<p>If you want to manipulate a string, consider <code>StringBuilder</code> or <code>StringBuffer</code> in case you require thread safety.</p>\n"
  }, {
